                <pb n="1"/>
            <p>A preface to a discourse for 2 Bar Mitzv&#225;<lb/></p>
            
            <p>I can imagine the spiritual joy of fathers and mothers<lb/> in Israel&#44; when after thirteen years of diligent training&#44;<lb/> they cause their sons to stand before the ark of the Lord&#44;<lb/> as an evidence of their fidelity to the discharge of parental<lb/> duties.  Could they give then utterance to their feelings&#44;<lb/> methinks they would thus exclaim.  O God&#33;  The creatures<lb/> over whom Thou hast appointed us natural guardians<lb/> we have endeavoured to rear in the knowledge of Thee.<lb/>  And now let the voluntary performance of their first<lb/> religious rig rite&#44; deepen into their minds the lessons we<lb/> early imparted&#44; and be initiatory of an uninterrupted fulfilling<lb/> of Thy sacred precepts&#44; all the days allotted to them upon earth.<lb/></p>  
            <p>My friends&#44; parents of our two Bar Mitzv&#225;&#33;  Have I represented<lb/> your feelings correctly&#44; or have I judged you erroneously&#63;<lb/>  I have based my opinion upon the ideas which I entertain<lb/> of the significance of the ceremony through which your young<lb/> sons have gone in this consecrated spot.  Let me not<lb/> be deprived of the hope that I have rightly interpreted your<lb/> motive.  Let me not harbour of any misgiving as<lb/> to the source of the gratification you experience<lb/></p>
            
            <pb n="2"/>
            <p>For were it to spring from human vanity&#44; then this event<lb/> would prove fruitless&#44; nay&#58; it might be fraught with<lb/> mischief&#44; because your children&#39;s hearts would&#44; like yours<lb/> swell with vainglory&#44; always attended with ill&#45;effects.<lb/>  Whereas this day occurrence you celebrate&#44; should be an incentive to<lb/> further exertions on your their part and on yours&#44; to gain the<lb/> approval of God&#44; they might be intpret disqualified<lb/> from imbibing religious teaching&#44; and you be rendered<lb/> heedless as to their future improvement in the know&#45;<lb/>&#45;ledge of their ancient faith.<lb/></p>
            
            <p>The rest of the discourse was made up at the time&#44; concluding<lb/> with the priestly blessing enlarged upon&#44; it being Sabbath of<lb/> Parashat Nasso<lb/></p>
            </body>
